386→                        <div id="content">Let $Y(x)$ be the maximal $y$ such that there exists a choice of congruence classes $a_p$ for all primes $p\leq x$ such that every integer in $[1,y]$ is congruent to at least one of the $a_p\pmod{p}$. <br><br>Give good estimates for $Y(x)$. In particular, can one prove that $Y(x)=o(x^2)$ or even $Y(x)\ll x^{1+o(1)}$?</div>
387→                        <div id="problem_id"><a href="/687">#687</a>: <a href="#cite-Er79d-687" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er79d','687'); return false;">[Er79d,p.79]</a><a href="#cite-Er80-687" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er80','687'); return false;">[Er80,p.106]</a><a href="#cite-Er96b-687" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er96b','687'); return false;">[Er96b]</a></div>
